<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sticker Situation: Louisiana could become the first state in the nation to make 
it illegal to sell "explicit" records without a warning label on them. A bill 
that would mandate the stickering of albums with explicit lyrics and prohibit 
the sale of such records to minors passed the Senate Judiciary Committee on 
Tuesday. The measure, which passed the Louisiana House of Representatives on 
May 14 , could be put to a floor vote in the Senate before the end of the week. 
GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
