<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: PASADENA; 
</P>
<P>
REOPENING ENTRANCE AT MUIR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A group of former John Muir High School students and faculty have approached 
the Board of Directors for support in reopening the school's front entrance on 
Lincoln Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
The entrance was walled off more than 20 years ago to control access to the 
school. 
</P>
<P>
Students enter the school through the faculty parking lot on the south side of 
the building. 
</P>
<P>
"Reopening the entrance would have a very positive impact on the Northwest 
revitalization goals," said Director Rick Cole. He said the closing of the 
entrance had been perceived as the school's "turning its back on the 
community." 
</P>
<P>
Director Kathryn Nack said the closing "might have been appropriate at that 
time, but certainly times are different now." 
</P>
<P>
A decision on the opening would be up to the Pasadena Unified School District 
board, but money would probably have to come from the city, Cole said. The 
cost, which would include unsealing windows facing Lincoln Avenue, has been 
estimated at $230,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
