<HEADLINE>
<P>
BELIEF IN GODDESS FAILS TO SPARE STORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KALAPANA, Hawaii 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Offerings to the Hawaiian volcano goddess failed to save the Kalapana Store 
&amp; Drive-Inn, which succumbed Wednesday to lava flowing from Kilauea 
Volcano. 
</P>
<P>
Owner Walter Yamaguchi, 82, had proclaimed that his store would be untouched by 
the lava because of his special relationship with the volcano goddess Pele. 
</P>
<P>
But, before dawn, a lava finger extending from the flow engulfed the building, 
Civil Defense officials said. 
</P>
<P>
"Well, what can you do?" Yamaguchi said. "Pele, she made me collect the 
insurance. If no burn, I don't collect." 
</P>
<P>
No other structures in the now-deserted community were hit Wednesday as lava 
continued to pour from the Kupaianaha vent at a rate of 650,000 cubic meters a 
day, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Lava flowed into the ocean near the site of the Puna Canoe Club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
