<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
IACOCCA SAYS HE'LL STAY IN POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee A. Iacocca declared today that he will stay in his 
post as head of the nation's No. 3 car company after his current contract 
expires in December, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
"When I came to Chrysler, I enlisted for the duration," Iacocca said in a press 
release. "Right now there's a battle raging and I'm not going to leave my 
troops in the field." 
</P>
<P>
The company last week lost its second-in-command and heir-apparent to Iacocca 
when Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald left to head the employee group bidding for 
UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, for $4.4 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
