<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DON'T BASH JAPAN, DELEGATE SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
FOREST GROVE, Ore. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Japanese business leader said the United States should "stop whining" about 
Japan's trade barriers and stop "bashing Japan as a scapegoat" for America's 
own economic problems. 
</P>
<P>
Tadashi Yamamoto, president and chairperson of the Japan Center for 
International Exchange, made the remarks at the final day of Pacific 
University's First Pacific Symposium. 
</P>
<P>
Yamamoto said he was worried about negative feelings toward Japan in the United 
States. A poll presented to delegates by Rep. Les AuCoin (D-Ore.) showed his 
constituents resent the Japanese. 
</P>
<P>
"The negative feelings for Japan have slipped out of the beltway and into such 
hospitable communities as Portland, which is reason for grave concerns by the 
Japanese," Yamamoto said. 
</P>
<P>
Yamamoto added, however, that he is leaving the symposium with a great optimism 
about future ties between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
